[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] This differs only in that it contains the empty string while the original grammar did not.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Here, the nonterminal *T* can generate all strings with more as than bs, the nonterminal *U* generates all strings with more bs than as and the nonterminal *V* generates all strings with an equal number of as and bs.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Omitting the third alternative in the rules for *T* and *U* does not restrict the grammar's language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] The formation rules for the terms and formulas of formal logic fit the definition of context-free grammar, except that the set of symbols may be infinite and there may be more than one start symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] The fact that this language is not context-free can be proven using pumping lemma for context-free languages and a proof by contradiction, observing that all words of the form ${(}^{n}{[}^{n}{)}^{n}{]}^{n}$ should belong to the language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] This language belongs instead to a more general class and can be described by a conjunctive grammar, which in turn also includes other non-context-free languages, such as the language of all words of the form a*n*b*n*c*n*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Every regular grammar is context-free, but not all context-free grammars are regular.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] The following context-free grammar, for example, is also regular.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] The terminals here are a and b, while the only nonterminal is *S*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] The language described is all nonempty strings of as and bs that end in a.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] This grammar is regular: no rule has more than one nonterminal in its right-hand side, and each of these nonterminals is at the same end of the right-hand side.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Every regular grammar corresponds directly to a nondeterministic finite automaton, so we know that this is a regular language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] A *derivation* of a string for a grammar is a sequence of grammar rule applications that transform the start symbol into the string.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] A derivation proves that the string belongs to the grammar's language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] For clarity, the intermediate string is usually given as well.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Given such a strategy, a derivation is completely determined by the sequence of rules applied.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] The distinction between leftmost derivation and rightmost derivation is important because in most parsers the transformation of the input is defined by giving a piece of code for every grammar rule that is executed whenever the rule is applied.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Therefore, it is important to know whether the parser determines a leftmost or a rightmost derivation because this determines the order in which the pieces of code will be executed.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] See for an example LL parsers and LR parsers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] A derivation also imposes in some sense a hierarchical structure on the string that is derived.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] where {...}*S* denotes a substring recognized as belonging to *S*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] This tree is called a *parse tree* or "concrete syntax tree" of the string, by contrast with the abstract syntax tree.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Note however that both parse trees can be obtained by both leftmost and rightmost derivations.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] If a string in the language of the grammar has more than one parsing tree, then the grammar is said to be an *ambiguous grammar*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Such grammars are usually hard to parse because the parser cannot always decide which grammar rule it has to apply.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Usually, ambiguity is a feature of the grammar, not the language, and an unambiguous grammar can be found that generates the same context-free language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] However, there are certain languages that can only be generated by ambiguous grammars; such languages are called *inherently ambiguous languages*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Every context-free grammar with no ε-production has an equivalent grammar in Chomsky normal form, and a grammar in Greibach normal form.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] "Equivalent" here means that the two grammars generate the same language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] The especially simple form of production rules in Chomsky normal form grammars has both theoretical and practical implications.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] For instance, given a context-free grammar, one can use the Chomsky normal form to construct a polynomial-time algorithm that decides whether a given string is in the language represented by that grammar or not (the CYK algorithm).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] They are not closed under general intersection (hence neither under complementation) and set difference.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] The following are some decidable problems about context-free grammars.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Context-free parsing for Chomsky normal form grammars was shown by Leslie G.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Valiant to be reducible to Boolean matrix multiplication, thus inheriting its complexity upper bound of *O*(*n*2.3728639).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Conversely, Lillian Lee has shown *O*(*n*3−*ε*) Boolean matrix multiplication to be reducible to *O*(*n*3−3*ε*) CFG parsing, thus establishing some kind of lower bound for the latter.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] A nonterminal symbol X is called *productive*, or *generating*, if there is a derivation $X~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~w$ for some string w of terminal symbols.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] X is called *reachable* if there is a derivation $S~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~\alpha X\beta$ for some strings $\alpha ,\beta$ of nonterminal and terminal symbols from the start symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] X is called *useless* if it is unreachable or unproductive.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] X is called *nullable* if there is a derivation $X~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~\varepsilon$ .
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] A rule $X\rightarrow \varepsilon$ is called an *ε-production*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] A derivation $X~{\stackrel {+}{\Rightarrow }}~X$ is called a *cycle*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] In particular, an alternative containing a useless nonterminal symbol can be deleted from the right-hand side of a rule.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Such rules and alternatives are called *useless*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] In the depicted example grammar, the nonterminal *D* is unreachable, and *E* is unproductive, while *C* → *C* causes a cycle.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Hence, omitting the last three rules does not change the language generated by the grammar, nor does omitting the alternatives "| *C*c | *E*e" from the right-hand side of the rule for *S*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] A context-free grammar is said to be *proper* if it has neither useless symbols nor ε-productions nor cycles.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Combining the above algorithms, every context-free grammar not generating ε can be transformed into a weakly equivalent proper one.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] It is decidable whether a given *grammar* is a regular grammar, as well as whether it is an LL(*k*) grammar for a given *k* ≥ 0.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] If *k* is not given, the latter problem is undecidable.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Given a context-free grammar, it is not decidable whether its language is regular, nor whether it is an LL(*k*) language for a given *k*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] There are algorithms to decide whether the language of a given context-free grammar is empty, as well as whether it is finite.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Some questions that are undecidable for wider classes of grammars become decidable for context-free grammars; e.g. the emptiness problem (whether the grammar generates any terminal strings at all), is undecidable for context-sensitive grammars, but decidable for context-free grammars.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] However, many problems are undecidable even for context-free grammars; the most prominent ones are handled in the following.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Given a CFG, does it generate the language of all strings over the alphabet of terminal symbols used in its rules?
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] A reduction can be demonstrated to this problem from the well-known undecidable problem of determining whether a Turing machine accepts a particular input (the halting problem).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] The reduction uses the concept of a *computation history*, a string describing an entire computation of a Turing machine.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] A CFG can be constructed that generates all strings that are not accepting computation histories for a particular Turing machine on a particular input, and thus it will accept all strings only if the machine does not accept that input.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Given two CFGs, do they generate the same language?
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] The undecidability of this problem is a direct consequence of the previous: it is impossible to even decide whether a CFG is equivalent to the trivial CFG defining the language of all strings.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Given two CFGs, can the first one generate all strings that the second one can generate?
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] If this problem was decidable, then language equality could be decided too: two CFGs $G_{1}$ and $G_{2}$ generate the same language if $L(G_{1})$ is a subset of $L(G_{2})$ and $L(G_{2})$ is a subset of $L(G_{1})$ .
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] The undecidability of this problem follows from the fact that if an algorithm to determine ambiguity existed, the Post correspondence problem could be decided, which is known to be undecidable.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Given two CFGs, is there any string derivable from both grammars?
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Then the PCP instance given by $\alpha _{1},\ldots ,\alpha _{N},\beta _{1},\ldots ,\beta _{N}$ has a solution if and only if ⁠ $L(G_{1})$ ⁠ and ⁠ $L(G_{2})$ ⁠ share a derivable string.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] The left of the string (before the b ) will represent the top of the solution for the PCP instance while the right side will be the bottom in reverse.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] An obvious way to extend the context-free grammar formalism is to allow nonterminals to have arguments, the values of which are passed along within the rules.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] This allows natural language features such as agreement and reference, and programming language analogs such as the correct use and definition of identifiers, to be expressed in a natural way.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] E.g. we can now easily express that in English sentences, the subject and verb must agree in number.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] In computer science, examples of this approach include affix grammars, attribute grammars, indexed grammars, and Van Wijngaarden two-level grammars.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Similar extensions exist in linguistics.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] An **extended context-free grammar** (or **regular right part grammar**) is one in which the right-hand side of the production rules is allowed to be a regular expression over the grammar's terminals and nonterminals.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Extended context-free grammars describe exactly the context-free languages.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Another extension is to allow additional terminal symbols to appear at the left-hand side of rules, constraining their application.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] This produces the formalism of context-sensitive grammars.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] LR parsing extends LL parsing to support a larger range of grammars; in turn, generalized LR parsing extends LR parsing to support arbitrary context-free grammars.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] On LL grammars and LR grammars, it essentially performs LL parsing and LR parsing, respectively, while on nondeterministic grammars, it is as efficient as can be expected.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Although GLR parsing was developed in the 1980s, many new language definitions and parser generators continue to be based on LL, LALR or LR parsing up to the present day.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Chomsky initially hoped to overcome the limitations of context-free grammars by adding transformation rules.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Such rules are another standard device in traditional linguistics; e.g. passivization in English.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Much of generative grammar has been devoted to finding ways of refining the descriptive mechanisms of phrase-structure grammar and transformation rules such that exactly the kinds of things can be expressed that natural language actually allows.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Allowing arbitrary transformations does not meet that goal: they are much too powerful, being Turing complete unless significant restrictions are added (e.g. no transformations that introduce and then rewrite symbols in a context-free fashion).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Chomsky's general position regarding the non-context-freeness of natural language has held up since then, although his specific examples regarding the inadequacy of context-free grammars in terms of their weak generative capacity were later disproved.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/context-free-grammar] Gerald Gazdar and Geoffrey Pullum have argued that despite a few non-context-free constructions in natural language (such as cross-serial dependencies in Swiss German and reduplication in Bambara), the vast majority of forms in natural language are indeed context-free.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] In computer science, **garbage collection** (**GC**) is a form of automatic memory management.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] The *garbage collector* attempts to reclaim memory that was allocated by the program, but is no longer referenced; such memory is called *garbage*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection was invented by American computer scientist John McCarthy around 1959 to simplify manual memory management in Lisp.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection relieves the programmer from doing manual memory management, where the programmer specifies what objects to de-allocate and return to the memory system and when to do so.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other, similar techniques include stack allocation, region inference, and memory ownership, and combinations thereof.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection may take a significant proportion of a program's total processing time, and affect performance as a result.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Resources other than memory, such as network sockets, database handles, windows, file descriptors, and device descriptors, are not typically handled by garbage collection, but rather by other methods (e.g. destructors).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some such methods de-allocate memory also.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Many programming languages require garbage collection, either as part of the language specification (e.g., RPL, Java, C#, D, Go, and most scripting languages) or effectively for practical implementation (e.g., formal languages like lambda calculus).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] These are said to be *garbage-collected languages*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other languages, such as C and C++, were designed for use with manual memory management, but have garbage-collected implementations available.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some languages, like Ada, Modula-3, and C++/CLI, allow both garbage collection and manual memory management to co-exist in the same application by using separate heaps for collected and manually managed objects.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Still others, like D, are garbage-collected but allow the user to manually delete objects or even disable garbage collection entirely when speed is required.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Although many languages integrate GC into their compiler and runtime system, *post-hoc* GC systems also exist, such as Automatic Reference Counting (ARC).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some of these *post-hoc* GC systems do not require recompilation.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] GC frees the programmer from manually de-allocating memory.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] GC uses computing resources to decide which memory to free.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Therefore, the penalty for the convenience of not annotating object lifetime manually in the source code is overhead, which can impair program performance.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] A peer-reviewed paper from 2005 concluded that GC needs five times the memory to compensate for this overhead and to perform as fast as the same program using idealized explicit memory management.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] The comparison however is made to a program generated by inserting deallocation calls using an oracle, implemented by collecting traces from programs run under a profiler, and the program is only correct for one particular execution of the program.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Interaction with memory hierarchy effects can make this overhead intolerable in circumstances that are hard to predict or to detect in routine testing.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] The impact on performance was given by Apple as a reason for not adopting garbage collection in iOS, despite it being the most desired feature.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] The moment when the garbage is actually collected can be unpredictable, resulting in stalls (pauses to shift/free memory) scattered throughout a session.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Unpredictable stalls can be unacceptable in real-time environments, in transaction processing, or in interactive programs.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Incremental, concurrent, and real-time garbage collectors address these problems, with varying trade-offs.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Tracing garbage collection is the most common type of garbage collection, so much so that "garbage collection" often refers to tracing garbage collection, rather than other methods such as reference counting.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] The overall strategy consists of determining which objects should be garbage collected by tracing which objects are *reachable* by a chain of references from certain root objects, and considering the rest as garbage and collecting them.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, there are a large number of algorithms used in implementation, with widely varying complexity and performance characteristics.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Reference counting garbage collection is where each object has a count of the number of references to it.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage is identified by having a reference count of zero.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] An object's reference count is incremented when a reference to it is created and decremented when a reference is destroyed.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] When the count reaches zero, the object's memory is reclaimed.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] If two or more objects refer to each other, they can create a cycle whereby neither will be collected as their mutual references never let their reference counts become zero.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] ) use specific cycle-detecting algorithms to deal with this issue.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] for the "backpointers" which create cycles.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Under reference counting, a weak reference is similar to a weak reference under a tracing garbage collector.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] It is a special reference object whose existence does not increment the reference count of the referent object.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] , rather than being permitted to remain dangling, meaning that it turns into a predictable value, such as a null reference.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Reference counting requires space to be allocated for each object to store its reference count.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] The count may be stored adjacent to the object's memory or in a side table somewhere else, but in either case, every single reference-counted object requires additional storage for its reference count.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Memory space with the size of an unsigned pointer is commonly used for this task, meaning that 32 or 64 bits of reference count storage must be allocated for each object.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] to store the reference count in unused areas of the object's memory.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Often, an architecture does not actually allow programs to access the full range of memory addresses that could be stored in its native pointer size; a certain number of high bits in the address is either ignored or required to be zero.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] If an object reliably has a pointer at a certain location, the reference count can be stored in the unused bits of the pointer.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] , 19 unused bits of this class pointer are used to store the object's reference count.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] In naive implementations, each assignment of a reference and each reference falling out of scope often require modifications of one or more reference counters.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, in a common case when a reference is copied from an outer scope variable into an inner scope variable, such that the lifetime of the inner variable is bounded by the lifetime of the outer one, the reference incrementing can be eliminated.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] The outer variable "owns" the reference.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] whose constructors, destructors, and assignment operators manage the references.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] A smart pointer can be passed by reference to a function, which avoids the need to copy-construct a new smart pointer (which would increase the reference count on entry into the function and decrease it on exit).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Instead, the function receives a reference to the smart pointer which is produced inexpensively.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] The Deutsch-Bobrow method of reference counting capitalizes on the fact that most reference count updates are in fact generated by references stored in local variables.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] It ignores these references, only counting references in the heap, but before an object with reference count zero can be deleted, the system must verify with a scan of the stack and register that no other reference to it still exists.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Consider a pointer that in a given interval of the execution is updated several times.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] But most of these updates are redundant.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Levanoni and Petrank measured an elimination of more than 99% of the counter updates in typical Java benchmarks.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] , at least for any objects which are shared, or potentially shared among multiple threads.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Atomic operations are expensive on a multiprocessor, and even more expensive if they have to be emulated with software algorithms.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] can be used to eliminate all atomic operations from the write-barrier.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Counters are never updated by the program threads in the course of program execution.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] They are only modified by the collector which executes as a single additional thread with no synchronization.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] This method can be used as a stop-the-world mechanism for parallel programs, and also with a concurrent reference counting collector.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Naive implementations of reference counting do not generally provide real-time behavior, because any pointer assignment can potentially cause a number of objects bounded only by total allocated memory size to be recursively freed while the thread is unable to perform other work.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] It is possible to avoid this issue by delegating the freeing of unreferenced objects to other threads, at the cost of extra overhead.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Escape analysis is a compile-time technique that can convert heap allocations to stack allocations, thereby reducing the amount of garbage collection to be done.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] This analysis determines whether an object allocated inside a function is accessible outside of it.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] If a function-local allocation is found to be accessible to another function or thread, the allocation is said to "escape" and cannot be done on the stack.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Otherwise, the object may be allocated directly on the stack and released when the function returns, bypassing the heap and associated memory management costs.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Generally speaking, higher-level programming languages are more likely to have garbage collection as a standard feature.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] In some languages lacking built-in garbage collection, it can be added through a library, as with the Boehm garbage collector for C and C++.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Most functional programming languages, such as ML, Haskell, and APL, have garbage collection built in.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Lisp is especially notable as both the first functional programming language and the first language to introduce garbage collection.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other dynamic languages, such as Ruby and Julia (but not Perl 5 or PHP before version 5.3, which both use reference counting), JavaScript and ECMAScript also tend to use GC.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Object-oriented programming languages such as Smalltalk, ooRexx, RPL and Java usually provide integrated garbage collection.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Notable exceptions are C++ and Delphi, which have destructors.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] BASIC and Logo have often used garbage collection for variable-length data types, such as strings and lists, so as not to burden programmers with memory management details.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] On the Altair 8800, programs with many string variables and little string space could cause long pauses due to garbage collection.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Similarly the Applesoft BASIC interpreter's garbage collection algorithm repeatedly scans the string descriptors for the string having the highest address in order to compact it toward high memory, resulting in $O(n^{2})$ performance and pauses anywhere from a few seconds to a few minutes.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] A replacement garbage collector for Applesoft BASIC by Randy Wigginton identifies a group of strings in every pass over the heap, reducing collection time dramatically.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] BASIC.SYSTEM, released with ProDOS in 1983, provides a windowing garbage collector for BASIC that is many times faster.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] C has never offered official support for garbage collection.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] C++ added garbage collection support in C++11 to the standard library, however this was removed in C++23 due to no compilers implementing support for the feature.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] The features that were part of this were related to pointer safety.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Although garbage collection support in the standard library was removed, some garbage collectors such as Boehm garbage collector (for C and C++) can still be used.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Boehm GC uses mark-and-sweep garbage collection.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] It can also be used in leak detection mode, where memory management is still manual however leaks and double-free errors can be detected and reported.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Its use can be called from the header `<gc.h>`.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] One can still abstract away manual object destructions in C++ by using the "resource acquisition is initialization" (RAII) idiom and smart pointers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] `std::unique_ptr` ties lifetimes to ownership, while `std::shared_ptr` uses reference counting to determine lifetime.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] `std::weak_ptr` can be used to obtain a pointer without increasing the reference count.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Unlike garbage collection, RAII is deterministic.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] While the Objective-C traditionally had no garbage collection, with the release of OS X 10.5 in 2007 Apple introduced garbage collection for Objective-C 2.0, using an in-house developed runtime collector.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, with the 2012 release of OS X 10.8, garbage collection was deprecated in favor of LLVM's automatic reference counter (ARC) that was introduced with OS X 10.7.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Furthermore, since May 2015 Apple even forbade the usage of garbage collection for new OS X applications in the App Store.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] For iOS, garbage collection has never been introduced due to problems in application responsivity and performance; instead, iOS uses ARC.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection is rarely used on embedded or real-time systems because of the usual need for very tight control over the use of limited resources.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, garbage collectors compatible with many limited environments have been developed.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] The Microsoft .NET Micro Framework, .NET nanoFramework and Java Platform, Micro Edition are embedded software platforms that, like their larger cousins, include garbage collection.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Compile-time garbage collection is a form of static analysis allowing memory to be reused and reclaimed based on invariants known during compilation.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] This form of garbage collection has been studied in the Mercury programming language, and it saw greater usage with the introduction of LLVM's automatic reference counter (ARC) into Apple's ecosystem (iOS and OS X) in 2011.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Incremental, concurrent, and real-time garbage collectors have been developed, for example by Henry Baker and by Henry Lieberman.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] In Baker's algorithm, the allocation is done in either half of a single region of memory.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] When it becomes half full, a garbage collection is performed which moves the live objects into the other half and the remaining objects are implicitly deallocated.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] The running program (the 'mutator') has to check that any object it references is in the correct half, and if not move it across, while a background task is finding all of the objects.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Generational garbage collection schemes are based on the empirical observation that most objects die young.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] In generational garbage collection, two or more allocation regions (generations) are kept, which are kept separate based on the object's age.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] New objects are created in the "young" generation that is regularly collected, and when a generation is full, the objects that are still referenced from older regions are copied into the next oldest generation.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some high-level language computer architectures include hardware support for real-time garbage collection.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Most implementations of real-time garbage collectors use tracing.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/garbage-collection-computer-science] Such real-time garbage collectors meet hard real-time constraints when used with a real-time operating system.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] An **intermediate representation** (**IR**) is the data structure or code used internally by a compiler or virtual machine to represent source code.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] An IR is designed to be conducive to further processing, such as optimization and translation.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] A "good" IR must be *accurate* – capable of representing the source code without loss of information – and *independent* of any particular source or target language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] An IR may take one of several forms: an in-memory data structure, or a special tuple- or stack-based code readable by the program.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] In the latter case it is also called an *intermediate language*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] A canonical example is found in most modern compilers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] For example, the CPython interpreter transforms the linear human-readable text representing a program into an intermediate graph structure that allows flow analysis and re-arrangement before execution.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] Use of an intermediate representation such as this allows compiler systems like the GNU Compiler Collection and LLVM to be used by many different source languages to generate code for many different target architectures.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] An **intermediate language** is the language of an abstract machine designed to aid in the analysis of computer programs.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] The term comes from their use in compilers, where the source code of a program is translated into a form more suitable for code-improving transformations before being used to generate object or machine code for a target machine.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] A popular format for intermediate languages is three-address code.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] The term is also used to refer to languages used as intermediates by some high-level programming languages which do not output object or machine code themselves, but output the intermediate language only.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] This intermediate language is submitted to a compiler for such language, which then outputs finished object or machine code.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] This is usually done to ease the process of optimization or to increase portability by using an intermediate language that has compilers for many processors and operating systems, such as C.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] Languages used for this fall in complexity between high-level languages and low-level languages, such as assembly languages.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] Variants of C have been designed to provide C's features as a portable assembly language, including C-- and the C Intermediate Language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] The GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) uses several intermediate languages internally to simplify portability and cross-compilation.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] The LLVM compiler framework is based on the LLVM IR intermediate language, of which the compact, binary serialized representation is also referred to as "bitcode" and has been productized by Apple.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] Like GIMPLE Bytecode, LLVM Bitcode is useful in link-time optimization.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] Like GCC, LLVM also targets some IRs meant for direct distribution, including Google's PNaCl IR and SPIR.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] A further development within LLVM is the use of *Multi-Level Intermediate Representation* (MLIR) with the potential to generate code for different heterogeneous targets, and to combine the outputs of different compilers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] The ILOC intermediate language is used in classes on compiler design as a simple target language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] Static analysis tools often use an intermediate representation.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] For instance, Radare2 is a toolbox for binary files analysis and reverse-engineering.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/intermediate-representation] It uses the intermediate languages ESIL and REIL to analyze binary files.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a combination of the two traditional approaches to translation to machine code: ahead-of-time compilation (AOT), and interpretation, which combines some advantages and drawbacks of both.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Roughly, JIT compilation combines the speed of compiled code with the flexibility of interpretation, with the overhead of an interpreter and the additional overhead of compiling and linking (not just interpreting).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a form of dynamic compilation, and allows adaptive optimization such as dynamic recompilation and microarchitecture-specific speedups.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Interpretation and JIT compilation are particularly suited for dynamic programming languages, as the runtime system can handle late-bound data types and enforce security guarantees.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] The earliest published JIT compiler is generally attributed to work on LISP by John McCarthy in 1960.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Another early example was by Ken Thompson, who in 1968 gave one of the first applications of regular expressions, here for pattern matching in the text editor QED.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by JITing to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] An influential technique for deriving compiled code from interpretation was pioneered by James G.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Mitchell in 1970, which he implemented for the experimental language *LC²*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] 1980) pioneered new aspects of JIT compilations.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] For example, translation to machine code was done on demand, and the result was cached for later use.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] When memory became scarce, the system would delete some of this code and regenerate it when it was needed again.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Sun's Self language improved these techniques extensively and was at one point the fastest Smalltalk system in the world, achieving up to half the speed of optimized C but with a fully object-oriented programming language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Self was abandoned by Sun, but the research went into the Java language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] The term "Just-in-time compilation" was borrowed from the manufacturing term "Just in time" and popularized by Java, with James Gosling using the term from 1993.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Currently JITing is used by most implementations of the Java virtual machine, as HotSpot builds on, and extensively uses, this research base.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] The HP project Dynamo was an experimental JIT compiler where the "bytecode" format and the machine code format were the same; the system optimized PA-8000 machine code.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] In November 2020, PHP 8.0 introduced a JIT compiler.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] In October 2024, CPython introduced an experimental JIT compiler.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] In a bytecode-compiled system, source code is translated to an intermediate representation known as bytecode.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Bytecode is not the machine code for any particular computer, and may be portable among computer architectures.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] The bytecode may then be interpreted by, or run on a virtual machine.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] The JIT compiler reads the bytecodes in many sections (or in full, rarely) and compiles them dynamically into machine code so the program can run faster.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] This can be done per-file, per-function or even on any arbitrary code fragment; the code can be compiled when it is about to be executed (hence the name "just-in-time"), and then cached and reused later without needing to be recompiled.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] By contrast, a traditional *interpreted virtual machine* will simply interpret the bytecode, generally with much lower performance.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Some *interpreter*s even interpret source code, without the step of first compiling to bytecode, with even worse performance.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] *Statically-compiled code* or *native code* is compiled prior to deployment.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] A *dynamic compilation environment* is one in which the compiler can be used during execution.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] The deployed bytecode is portable, unlike native code.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Since the runtime has control over the compilation, like interpreted bytecode, it can run in a secure sandbox.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Compilers from bytecode to machine code are easier to write, because the portable bytecode compiler has already done much of the work.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] JIT code generally offers far better performance than interpreters.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] The system is able to collect statistics about how the program is actually running in the environment it is in, and it can rearrange and recompile for optimum performance.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] However, some static compilers can also take profile information as input.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] The system can do global code optimizations (e.g. inlining of library functions) without losing the advantages of dynamic linking and without the overheads inherent to static compilers and linkers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] With just-in-time compilation in many cases this processing can be moved out of loops, often giving large increases of speed.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Although this is possible with statically compiled garbage collected languages, a bytecode system can more easily rearrange executed code for better cache utilization.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] However, a special type of "JIT" may potentially *not* target the physical machine's CPU architecture, but rather an optimized VM bytecode where limitations on raw machine code prevail, especially where that bytecode's VM eventually leverages a JIT to native code.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] JIT causes a slight to noticeable delay in the initial execution of an application, due to the time taken to load and compile the input code.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Sometimes this delay is called "startup time delay" or "warm-up time".
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] In general, the more optimization JIT performs, the better the code it will generate, but the initial delay will also increase.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] A JIT compiler therefore has to make a trade-off between the compilation time and the quality of the code it hopes to generate.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Startup time can include increased IO-bound operations in addition to JIT compilation: for example, the *rt.jar* class data file for the Java virtual machine (JVM) is 40 MB and the JVM must seek a lot of data in this contextually huge file.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] One possible optimization, used by Sun's HotSpot Java virtual machine, is to combine interpretation and JIT compilation.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] The application code is initially interpreted, but the JVM monitors which sequences of bytecode are frequently executed and translates them to machine code for direct execution on the hardware.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] For bytecode which is executed only a few times, this saves the compilation time and reduces the initial latency; for frequently executed bytecode, JIT compilation is used to run at high speed, after an initial phase of slow interpretation.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Further, since a program spends most time executing a minority of its code, the reduced compilation time is significant.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Finally, during the initial code interpretation, execution statistics can be collected before compilation, which helps to perform better optimization.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] The correct tradeoff can vary due to circumstances.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] For example, Sun's Java virtual machine has two major modes—client and server.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] In client mode, minimal compilation and optimization is performed, to reduce startup time.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] In server mode, extensive compilation and optimization is performed, to maximize performance once the application is running by sacrificing startup time.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Other Java just-in-time compilers have used a runtime measurement of the number of times a method has executed combined with the bytecode size of a method as a heuristic to decide when to compile.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Still another uses the number of times executed combined with the detection of loops.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] In general, it is much harder to accurately predict which methods to optimize in short-running applications than in long-running ones.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Native Image Generator (Ngen) by Microsoft is another approach at reducing the initial delay.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Ngen pre-compiles (or "pre-JITs") bytecode in a Common Intermediate Language image into machine native code.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] As a result, no runtime compilation is needed. .NET Framework 2.0 shipped with Visual Studio 2005 runs Ngen on all of the Microsoft dynamic-link library (DLL) files right after installing.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Pre-jitting provides a way to reduce startup time.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] However, the quality of code it generates may be lower than the one that is JITed, for the same reasons why code compiled statically, without profile-guided optimization, cannot be as good as JIT compiled code in the extreme case: the lack of profiling data to drive, for instance, inline caching.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] There also exist Java implementations that combine an AOT (ahead-of-time) compiler with either a JIT compiler (Excelsior JET) or interpreter (GNU Compiler for Java).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation may not reliably achieve its goal, namely entering a steady state of improved performance after a short initial warmup period.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Across eight different virtual machines, Barrett et al.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] (2017) measured six widely used microbenchmarks which are commonly used by virtual machine implementors as optimisation targets, running them repeatedly within a single process execution.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Even where an improved steady-state was reached, it sometimes took many hundreds of iterations.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] (2022) instead focused on the HotSpot virtual machine but with a much wider array of benchmarks, finding that 10.9% of process executions failed to reach a steady state of performance, and 43.5% of benchmarks did not consistently attain a steady state across multiple executions.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation fundamentally uses executable data, and thus poses security challenges and possible exploits.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Implementation of JIT compilation consists of compiling source code or byte code to machine code and executing it.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] This is generally done directly in memory: the JIT compiler outputs the machine code directly into memory and immediately executes it, rather than outputting it to disk and then invoking the code as a separate program, as in usual ahead of time compilation.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] In modern architectures this runs into a problem due to executable space protection: arbitrary memory cannot be executed, as otherwise there is a potential security hole.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Thus memory must be marked as executable; for security reasons this should be done *after* the code has been written to memory, and marked read-only, as writable/executable memory is a security hole (see W^X).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] For instance Firefox's JIT compiler for JavaScript introduced this protection in a release version with Firefox 46.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] JIT spraying is a class of computer security exploits that use JIT compilation for heap spraying: the resulting memory is then executable, which allows an exploit if execution can be moved into the heap.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation can be applied to some programs, or can be used for certain capacities, particularly dynamic capacities such as regular expressions.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] For example, a text editor may compile a regular expression provided at runtime to machine code to allow faster matching: this cannot be done ahead of time, as the pattern is only provided at runtime.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Several modern runtime environments rely on JIT compilation for high-speed code execution, including most implementations of Java, together with Microsoft's .NET.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Similarly, many regular-expression libraries feature JIT compilation of regular expressions, either to bytecode or to machine code.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is also used in some emulators, in order to translate machine code from one CPU architecture to another.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] A common implementation of JIT compilation is to first have AOT compilation to bytecode (virtual machine code), known as *bytecode compilation*, and then have JIT compilation to machine code (dynamic compilation), rather than interpretation of the bytecode.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] This improves the runtime performance compared to interpretation, at the cost of lag due to compilation.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilers translate continuously, as with interpreters, but caching of compiled code minimizes lag on future execution of the same code during a given run.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/just-in-time-compilation] Since only part of the program is compiled, there is significantly less lag than if the entire program were compiled prior to execution.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] A rule-based program, performing lexical tokenization, is called *tokenizer*, or *scanner*, although *scanner* is also a term for the first stage of a lexer.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] A lexer forms the first phase of a compiler frontend in processing.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Lexers and parsers are most often used for compilers, but can be used for other computer language tools, such as prettyprinters or linters.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Lexing can be divided into two stages: the *scanning*, which segments the input string into syntactic units called *lexemes* and categorizes these into token classes, and the *evaluating*, which converts lexemes into processed values.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Lexers are generally quite simple, with most of the complexity deferred to the syntactic analysis or semantic analysis phases, and can often be generated by a lexer generator, notably lex or derivatives.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] However, lexers can sometimes include some complexity, such as phrase structure processing to make input easier and simplify the parser, and may be written partly or fully by hand, either to support more features or for performance.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing is not equal to what is called lexeme in linguistics.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing can be equal to the linguistic equivalent only in analytic languages, such as English, but not in highly synthetic languages, such as fusional languages.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] What is called a lexeme in rule-based natural language processing is more similar to what is called a word in linguistics (not to be confused with a word in computer architecture), although in some cases it may be more similar to a morpheme.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] A *lexical token* is a string with an assigned and thus identified meaning, in contrast to the probabilistic token used in large language models.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] A lexical token consists of a *token name* and an optional *token value*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The token name is a category of a rule-based lexical unit.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] A token name is what might be termed a part of speech in linguistics.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] the string is not implicitly segmented on spaces, as a natural language speaker would do.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The raw input, the 43 characters, must be explicitly split into the 9 tokens with a given space delimiter (i.e., matching the string `" "` or regular expression `/\s{1}/`).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] When a token class represents more than one possible lexeme, the lexer often saves enough information to reproduce the original lexeme, so that it can be used in semantic analysis.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The parser typically retrieves this information from the lexer and stores it in the abstract syntax tree.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] This is necessary in order to avoid information loss in the case where numbers may also be valid identifiers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Tokens are identified based on the specific rules of the lexer.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Some methods used to identify tokens include regular expressions, specific sequences of characters termed a flag, specific separating characters called delimiters, and explicit definition by a dictionary.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Special characters, including punctuation characters, are commonly used by lexers to identify tokens because of their natural use in written and programming languages.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] A lexical analyzer generally does nothing with combinations of tokens, a task left for a parser.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] For example, a typical lexical analyzer recognizes parentheses as tokens but does nothing to ensure that each "(" is matched with a ")".
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] When a lexer feeds tokens to the parser, the representation used is typically an enumerated type, which is a list of number representations.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] For example, "Identifier" can be represented with 0, "Assignment operator" with 1, "Addition operator" with 2, etc.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Tokens are often defined by regular expressions, which are understood by a lexical analyzer generator such as lex, or handcoded equivalent finite-state automata.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The lexical analyzer (generated automatically by a tool like lex or hand-crafted) reads in a stream of characters, identifies the lexemes in the stream, and categorizes them into tokens.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] If the lexer finds an invalid token, it will report an error.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] From there, the interpreted data may be loaded into data structures for general use, interpretation, or compiling.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The specification of a programming language often includes a set of rules, the lexical grammar, which defines the lexical syntax.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The lexical syntax is usually a regular language, with the grammar rules consisting of regular expressions; they define the set of possible character sequences (lexemes) of a token.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] A lexer recognizes strings, and for each kind of string found, the lexical program takes an action, most simply producing a token.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Two important common lexical categories are white space and comments.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] These are also defined in the grammar and processed by the lexer but may be discarded (not producing any tokens) and considered *non-significant*, at most separating two tokens (as in `if x` instead of `ifx`).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] There are two important exceptions to this.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] First, in off-side rule languages that delimit blocks with indenting, initial whitespace is significant, as it determines block structure, and is generally handled at the lexer level; see phrase structure, below.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Secondly, in some uses of lexers, comments and whitespace must be preserved – for examples, a prettyprinter also needs to output the comments and some debugging tools may provide messages to the programmer showing the original source code.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] In the 1960s, notably for ALGOL, whitespace and comments were eliminated as part of the line reconstruction phase (the initial phase of the compiler frontend), but this separate phase has been eliminated and these are now handled by the lexer.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The first stage, the *scanner*, is usually based on a finite-state machine (FSM).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] It has encoded within it information on the possible sequences of characters that can be contained within any of the tokens it handles (individual instances of these character sequences are termed lexemes).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] For example, an *integer* lexeme may contain any sequence of numerical digit characters.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] In some languages, the lexeme creation rules are more complex and may involve backtracking over previously read characters.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] For example, in C, one 'L' character is not enough to distinguish between an identifier that begins with 'L' and a wide-character string literal.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] A lexeme, however, is only a string of characters known to be of a certain kind (e.g., a string literal, a sequence of letters).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The second stage of a lexical analyzer, the *evaluator*, goes over the characters of the lexeme to produce a *value* containing relevant information for the parser.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The lexeme's type combined with its value is what properly constitutes a *token*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The value in the token can be whatever is deemed necessary for the parser to interpret a token of that type.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The evaluator may also suppress a lexeme entirely, concealing it from the parser, which is useful for whitespace and comments.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] This is practical if the list of tokens is small, but lexers generated by automated tooling as part of a compiler-compiler toolchain are more practical for a larger number of potential tokens.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] These tools generally accept regular expressions that describe the tokens allowed in the input stream.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Each regular expression is associated with a production rule in the lexical grammar of the programming language that evaluates the lexemes matching the regular expression.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] These tools may generate source code that can be compiled and executed or construct a state transition table for a finite-state machine (which is plugged into template code for compiling and executing).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Regular expressions compactly represent patterns that the characters in lexemes might follow.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] For example, for an English-based language, an IDENTIFIER token might be any English alphabetic character or an underscore, followed by any number of instances of ASCII alphanumeric characters and/or underscores.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] This could be represented compactly by the string `[a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z_0-9]*`.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] This means "any character a-z, A-Z or _, followed by 0 or more of a-z, A-Z, _ or 0-9".
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] It takes a full parser to recognize such patterns in their full generality.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] A parser can push parentheses on a stack and then try to pop them off and see if the stack is empty at the end (see example in the *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* book).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Typically, lexical tokenization occurs at the word level.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] However, it is sometimes difficult to define what is meant by a "word".
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] In languages that use inter-word spaces (such as most that use the Latin alphabet, and most programming languages), this approach is fairly straightforward.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] However, even here there are many edge cases such as contractions, hyphenated words, emoticons, and larger constructs such as URIs (which for some purposes may count as single tokens).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] A classic example is "New York-based", which a naive tokenizer may break at the space even though the better break is (arguably) at the hyphen.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Tokenization is particularly difficult for languages written in scriptio continua, which exhibit no word boundaries, such as Ancient Greek, Chinese, or Thai.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Agglutinative languages, such as Korean, also make tokenization tasks complicated.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Some ways to address the more difficult problems include developing more complex heuristics, querying a table of common special cases, or fitting the tokens to a language model that identifies collocations in a later processing step.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Lexers are often generated by a *lexer generator*, analogous to parser generators, and such tools often come together.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The most established is lex, paired with the yacc parser generator, or rather some of their many reimplementations, like flex (often paired with GNU Bison).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] These generators are a form of domain-specific language, taking in a lexical specification – generally regular expressions with some markup – and emitting a lexer.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] These tools yield very fast development, which is very important in early development, both to get a working lexer and because a language specification may change often.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Further, they often provide advanced features, such as pre- and post-conditions which are hard to program by hand.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] However, an automatically generated lexer may lack flexibility, and thus may require some manual modification, or an all-manually written lexer.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Lexer performance is a concern, and optimizing is worthwhile, more so in stable languages where the lexer runs very often (such as C or HTML). lex/flex-generated lexers are reasonably fast, but improvements of two to three times are possible using more tuned generators.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Hand-written lexers are sometimes used, but modern lexer generators produce faster lexers than most hand-coded ones.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The lex/flex family of generators uses a table-driven approach which is much less efficient than the directly coded approach.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] With the latter approach the generator produces an engine that directly jumps to follow-up states via goto statements.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Tools like re2c have proven to produce engines that are between two and three times faster than flex produced engines.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] It is in general difficult to hand-write analyzers that perform better than engines generated by these latter tools.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Lexical analysis mainly segments the input stream of characters into tokens, simply grouping the characters into pieces and categorizing them.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] However, the lexing may be significantly more complex; most simply, lexers may omit tokens or insert added tokens.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Omitting tokens, notably whitespace and comments, is very common when these are not needed by the compiler.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Less commonly, added tokens may be inserted.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] This is done mainly to group tokens into statements, or statements into blocks, to simplify the parser.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Line continuation is a feature of some languages where a newline is normally a statement terminator.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Most often, ending a line with a backslash (immediately followed by a newline) results in the line being *continued* – the following line is *joined* to the prior line.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] This is generally done in the lexer: The backslash and newline are discarded, rather than the newline being tokenized.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Examples include bash, other shell scripts and Python.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Many languages use the semicolon as a statement terminator.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Most often this is mandatory, but in some languages the semicolon is optional in many contexts.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] This is mainly done at the lexer level, where the lexer outputs a semicolon into the token stream, despite one not being present in the input character stream, and is termed *semicolon insertion* or *automatic semicolon insertion*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] In these cases, semicolons are part of the formal phrase grammar of the language, but may not be found in input text, as they can be inserted by the lexer.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Optional semicolons or other terminators or separators are also sometimes handled at the parser level, notably in the case of trailing commas or semicolons.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is a feature of BCPL and its distant descendant Go, though it is absent in B or C.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is present in JavaScript, though the rules are somewhat complex and much-criticized; to avoid bugs, some recommend always using semicolons, while others use initial semicolons, termed defensive semicolons, at the start of potentially ambiguous statements.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] The off-side rule (blocks determined by indenting) can be implemented in the lexer, as in Python, where increasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting an INDENT token and decreasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting one or more DEDENT tokens.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] These tokens correspond to the opening brace `{` and closing brace `}` in languages that use braces for blocks and means that the phrase grammar does not depend on whether braces or indenting are used.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] This requires that the lexer hold state, namely a stack of indent levels, and thus can detect changes in indenting when this changes, and thus the lexical grammar is not context-free: INDENT–DEDENT depend on the contextual information of prior indent levels.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Generally lexical grammars are context-free, or almost so, and thus require no looking back or ahead, or backtracking, which allows a simple, clean, and efficient implementation.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] This also allows simple one-way communication from lexer to parser, without needing any information flowing back to the lexer.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] These examples all only require lexical context, and while they complicate a lexer somewhat, they are invisible to the parser and later phases.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] A more complex example is the lexer hack in C, where the token class of a sequence of characters cannot be determined until the semantic analysis phase since typedef names and variable names are lexically identical but constitute different token classes.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] Thus in the hack, the lexer calls the semantic analyzer (say, symbol table) and checks if the sequence requires a typedef name.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lexical-analysis] In this case, information must flow back not from the parser only, but from the semantic analyzer back to the lexer, which complicates design.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] A **linker** or **link editor** is a computer program that combines intermediate software build files such as object and library files into a single executable file such as a program or library.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] A linker is often part of a toolchain that includes a compiler and/or assembler that generates intermediate files that the linker processes.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] The linker may be integrated with other toolchain tools such that the user does not interact with the linker directly.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] A simpler version that writes its output directly to memory is called the *loader*, though loading is typically considered a separate process.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Computer programs typically are composed of several parts or modules; these parts/modules do not need to be contained within a single object file, and in such cases refer to each other using symbols as addresses into other modules, which are mapped into memory addresses when linked for execution.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] While the process of linking is meant to ultimately combine these independent parts, there are many good reasons to develop those separately at the source-level.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Among these reasons are the ease of organizing several smaller pieces over a monolithic whole and the ability to better define the purpose and responsibilities of each individual piece, which is essential for managing complexity and increasing long-term maintainability in software architecture.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] For most compilers, each object file is the result of compiling one input source code file.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] When a program comprises multiple object files, the linker combines these files into a unified executable program, resolving the symbols as it goes along.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Linkers can take objects from a collection called a library or runtime library.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Most linkers do not include all the object files in a static library in the output executable; they include only those object files from the library that are referenced by other object files or libraries directly or indirectly.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] But for a shared library, the entire library has to be loaded during runtime as it is not known which functions or methods will be called during runtime.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Library linking may thus be an iterative process, with some referenced modules requiring additional modules to be linked, and so on.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Libraries exist for diverse purposes, and one or more system libraries are usually linked in by default.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] The linker also takes care of arranging the objects in a program's address space.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] This may involve *relocating* code that assumes a specific base address into another base.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Since a compiler seldom knows where an object will reside, it often assumes a fixed base location (for example, zero).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Relocating machine code may involve re-targeting absolute jumps, loads, and stores.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] The executable output by the linker may need another relocation pass when it is finally loaded into memory (just before execution).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] This pass is usually omitted on hardware offering virtual memory: every program is put into its own address space, so there is no conflict even if all programs load at the same base address.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] This pass may also be omitted if the executable is a position independent executable.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Additionally, in some operating systems, the same program handles both the jobs of linking and loading a program (dynamic linking).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Many operating system environments allow dynamic linking, deferring the resolution of some undefined symbols until a program is run.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] That means that the executable code still contains undefined symbols, plus a list of objects or libraries that will provide definitions for these.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Loading the program will load these objects/libraries as well, and perform a final linking.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Contained or virtual environments may further allow system administrators to mitigate or trade-off these individual pros and cons.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Static linking is the result of the linker copying all library routines used in the program into the executable image.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] This may require more disk space and memory than dynamic linking, but is more portable, since it does not require the presence of the library on the system where it runs.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Static linking also prevents "DLL hell", since each program includes exactly the versions of library routines that it requires, with no conflict with other programs.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] A program using just a few routines from a library does not require the entire library to be installed.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] As the compiler has no information on the layout of objects in the final output, it cannot take advantage of shorter or more efficient instructions that place a requirement on the address of another object.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] For example, a jump instruction can reference an absolute address or an offset from the current location, and the offset could be expressed with different lengths depending on the distance to the target.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] By first generating the most conservative instruction (usually the largest relative or absolute variant, depending on platform) and adding *relaxation hints*, it is possible to substitute shorter or more efficient instructions during the final link.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] In regard to jump optimizations this is also called *automatic jump-sizing*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] This step can be performed only after all input objects have been read and assigned temporary addresses; the **linker relaxation** pass subsequently reassigns addresses, which may in turn allow more potential relaxations to occur.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] In general, the substituted sequences are shorter, which allows this process to always converge on the best solution given a fixed order of objects; if this is not the case, relaxations can conflict, and the linker needs to weigh the advantages of either option.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] While instruction relaxation typically occurs at link-time, inner-module relaxation can already take place as part of the optimizing process at compile-time.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] In some cases, relaxation can also occur at load-time as part of the relocation process or combined with dynamic dead-code elimination techniques.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] In IBM System/360 through IBM Z mainframe operating systems such as OS/360 and its successors, this type of program is known as a *linkage editor*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] As the name implies a linkage *editor* has the additional capability of allowing the addition, replacement, and/or deletion of individual program sections.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] One advantage of this is that it allows a program to be maintained without having to keep all of the intermediate object files, or without having to re-compile program sections that haven't changed.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] It also permits program updates to be distributed in the form of small files (originally card decks), containing only the object module to be replaced.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] In such systems, object code is in the form and format of 80-byte punched-card images, so that updates can be introduced into a system using that medium.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] In later releases of OS/360 and in subsequent systems, load-modules contain additional data about versions of components modules, to create a traceable record of updates.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] It also allows one to add, change, or remove an overlay structure from an already linked load module.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] The term "linkage editor" should not be construed as implying that the program operates in a user-interactive mode like a text editor.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] It is intended for batch-mode execution, with the editing commands being supplied by the user in sequentially organized files, such as punched cards, DASD, or magnetic tape.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Early linkers gave users very limited control over the arrangement of generated output object files.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] As the target systems became more complex with different memory requirements, such as in embedded systems, it became necessary to give users control to generate output object files with their specific requirements such as defining base addresses of segments.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Linker control scripts were used for this.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] On Unix and Unix-like systems, the static linker is usually invoked via the command `ld` which is an abbreviation of *LoaDer* or *Link eDitor*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] The term "loader" was used to describe the process of loading external symbols from other programs during the process of linking.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] (This terminology has been used in other operating systems as well.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] GNU ld, part of the GNU Binary Utilities (binutils), is the GNU Project version of the Unix static linker.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] A *linker script* may be passed to GNU ld to exercise fine grain control of the linking process.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Two versions of ld are provided in binutils: the traditional GNU ld based on bfd, and a streamlined ELF-only version called gold.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] The LLVM project's linker, *lld*, is designed to be drop-in compatible, and may be used directly with the GNU compiler.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/linker-computing] Another drop-in replacement, mold, is a highly parallelized and faster alternative which is also supported by GNU tools.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] In computer science, an **LL parser** is a top-down parser for a restricted context-free language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] It parses the input from **L**eft to right, performing **L**eftmost derivation of the sentence.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] An LL parser is called an LL(*k*) parser if it uses *k* tokens of lookahead when parsing a sentence.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] A grammar is called an LL(*k*) grammar if an LL(*k*) parser can be constructed from it.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] A formal language is called an LL(*k*) language if it has an LL(*k*) grammar.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The set of LL(*k*) languages is properly contained in that of LL(*k*+1) languages, for each *k* ≥ 0.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] A corollary of this is that not all context-free languages can be recognized by an LL(*k*) parser.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] An LL parser is called LL-regular (LLR) if it parses an LL-regular language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The class of LLR grammars contains every LL(*k*) grammar for every *k*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] For every LLR grammar there exists an LLR parser that parses the grammar in linear time.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Two nomenclative outlier parser types are LL(*) and LL(finite).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] A parser is called LL(*)/LL(finite) if it uses the LL(*)/LL(finite) parsing strategy.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] LL(*) and LL(finite) parsers are functionally closer to PEG parsers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] An LL(finite) parser can parse an arbitrary LL(*k*) grammar optimally in the amount of lookahead and lookahead comparisons.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The class of grammars parsable by the LL(*) strategy encompasses some context-sensitive languages due to the use of syntactic and semantic predicates and has not been identified.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] It has been suggested that LL(*) parsers are better thought of as TDPL parsers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Against the popular misconception, LL(*) parsers are not LLR in general, and are guaranteed by construction to perform worse on average (super-linear against linear time) and far worse in the worst-case (exponential against linear time).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] LL grammars, particularly LL(1) grammars, are of great practical interest, as parsers for these grammars are easy to construct, and many computer languages are designed to be LL(1) for this reason.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] LL parsers may be table-based, i.e. similar to LR parsers, but LL grammars can also be parsed by recursive descent parsers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] According to Waite and Goos (1984), LL(*k*) grammars were introduced by Stearns and Lewis (1969).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] For a given context-free grammar, the parser attempts to find the leftmost derivation.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Generally, there are multiple possibilities when selecting a rule to expand the leftmost non-terminal.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] To be efficient, the parser must be able to make this choice deterministically when possible, without backtracking.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] For some grammars, it can do this by peeking on the unread input (without reading).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] In our example, if the parser knows that the next unread symbol is **(**, the only correct rule that can be used is 2.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Generally, an LL(*k*) parser can look ahead at *k* symbols.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] However, given a grammar, the problem of determining if there exists a LL(*k*) parser for some *k* that recognizes it is undecidable.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] For each *k*, there is a language that cannot be recognized by an LL(*k*) parser, but can be by an LL(*k* + 1) parser.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Let *G* be a context-free grammar and *k* ≥ 1.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] the following condition holds: the prefix of the string u of length k equals the prefix of the string v of length *k* implies $\beta =\gamma$ .
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] In this definition, S is the start symbol and A any non-terminal.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The already derived input w , and yet unread u and v are strings of terminals.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The Greek letters $\alpha$ , $\beta$ and $\gamma$ represent any string of both terminals and non-terminals (possibly empty).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The prefix length corresponds to the lookahead buffer size, and the definition says that this buffer is enough to distinguish between any two derivations of different words.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The LL(*k*) parser is a deterministic pushdown automaton with the ability to peek on the next *k* input symbols without reading.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] This peek capability can be emulated by storing the lookahead buffer contents in the finite state space, since both buffer and input alphabet are finite in size.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] As a result, this does not make the automaton more powerful, but is a convenient abstraction.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The parser stack initially contains the starting symbol above the EOI: [ S **$** ].
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] If the last symbol to be removed from the stack is the EOI, the parsing is successful; the automaton accepts via an empty stack.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The states and the transition function are not explicitly given; they are specified (generated) using a more convenient *parse table* instead.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] If the parser cannot perform a valid transition, the input is rejected (empty cells).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] To make the table more compact, only the non-terminal rows are commonly displayed, since the action is the same for terminals.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] An LL(1) parsing table for a grammar has a row for each of the non-terminals and a column for each terminal (including the special terminal, represented here as **$**, that is used to indicate the end of the input stream).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Each cell of the table may point to at most one rule of the grammar (identified by its number).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The algorithm to construct a parsing table is described in a later section, but first let's see how the parser uses the parsing table to process its input.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] In each step, the parser reads the next-available symbol from the input stream, and the top-most symbol from the stack.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] If the input symbol and the stack-top symbol match, the parser discards them both by moving to the next input symbol and popping the top-most symbol off the stack.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] This is repeated until the input symbol and top-most symbol on the stack do not match.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Thus, in its first step, the parser reads the input symbol '**(**' and the stack-top symbol 'S'.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The parsing table instruction comes from the column headed by the input symbol '**(**' and the row headed by the stack-top symbol 'S'; this cell contains '2', which instructs the parser to apply rule (2).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The parser has to rewrite 'S' to '**(** S **+** F **)**' on the stack by removing 'S' from stack and pushing ')', 'F', '**+**', 'S', '**(**' onto the stack, and this writes the rule number 2 to the output.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] In the second step, the parser removes the '**(**' from its input stream and from its stack, since they now match.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Now the parser has an '**a'** on its input stream and an 'S' as its stack top.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The parsing table instructs it to apply rule (1) from the grammar and write the rule number 1 to the output stream.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The parser now has an '**a'** on its input stream and an 'F' as its stack top.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The parsing table instructs it to apply rule (3) from the grammar and write the rule number 3 to the output stream.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The parser now has an '**a'** on the input stream and an '**a**' at its stack top.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Because they are the same, it removes it from the input stream and pops it from the top of the stack.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The parser then has an '**+**' on the input stream and '**+**' is at the top of the stack meaning, like with 'a', it is popped from the stack and removed from the input stream.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] In the next three steps the parser will replace 'F' on the stack by '**a**', write the rule number 3 to the output stream and remove the '**a**' and '**)**' from both the stack and the input stream.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The parser thus ends with '**$**' on both its stack and its input stream.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] These steps are repeated until the parser stops, and then it will have either completely parsed the input and written a leftmost derivation to the output stream or it will have reported an error.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] In order to fill the parsing table, we have to establish what grammar rule the parser should choose if it sees a nonterminal *A* on the top of its stack and a symbol *a* on its input stream.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] It is easy to see that such a rule should be of the form *A* → *w* and that the language corresponding to *w* should have at least one string starting with *a*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] For this purpose we define the *First-set* of *w*, written here as **Fi**(*w*), as the set of terminals that can be found at the start of some string in *w*, plus ε if the empty string also belongs to *w*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] 4. do steps 2 and 3 until all **Fi** sets stay the same.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] where, for sets of words *U* and *V*, the truncated product is defined by $U\cdot V=\{(uv):1\mid u\in U,v\in V\}$ , and w:1 denotes the initial length-1 prefix of words w of length 2 or more, or *w*, itself, if w has length 0 or 1.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Unfortunately, the First-sets are not sufficient to compute the parsing table.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] This is because a right-hand side *w* of a rule might ultimately be rewritten to the empty string.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] So the parser should also use the rule *A* → *w* if *ε* is in **Fi**(*w*) and it sees on the input stream a symbol that could follow *A*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Therefore, we also need the *Follow-set* of *A*, written as **Fo**(*A*) here, which is defined as the set of terminals *a* such that there is a string of symbols *αAaβ* that can be derived from the start symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] We use **$** as a special terminal indicating end of input stream, and *S* as start symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] 3. repeat step 2 until all **Fo** sets stay the same.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Now we can define exactly which rules will appear where in the parsing table.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] If the table contains at most one rule in every one of its cells, then the parser will always know which rule it has to use and can therefore parse strings without backtracking.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] It is in precisely this case that the grammar is called an *LL(1) grammar*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] where an input is suffixed by *k* end-markers **$**, to fully account for the *k* lookahead context.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] This approach eliminates special cases for ε, and can be applied equally well in the LL(1) case.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Until the mid-1990s, it was widely believed that LL(*k*) parsing (for *k* > 1) was impractical, since the parser table would have exponential size in *k* in the worst case.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] This perception changed gradually after the release of the Purdue Compiler Construction Tool Set around 1992, when it was demonstrated that many programming languages can be parsed efficiently by an LL(*k*) parser without triggering the worst-case behavior of the parser.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Moreover, in certain cases LL parsing is feasible even with unlimited lookahead.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] By contrast, traditional parser generators like yacc use LALR(1) parser tables to construct a restricted LR parser with a fixed one-token lookahead.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] As described in the introduction, LL(1) parsers recognize languages that have LL(1) grammars, which are a special case of context-free grammars; LL(1) parsers cannot recognize all context-free languages.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The LL(1) languages are a proper subset of the LR(1) languages, which in turn are a proper subset of all context-free languages.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] In order for a context-free grammar to be an LL(1) grammar, certain conflicts must not arise.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] FIRST(*A*) is defined as the set of terminals that can appear in the first position of any string derived from *A*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] FOLLOW(*B*) where *B* is any head of a rule of the form *B* → *wA*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The FIRST sets of two different grammar rules for the same non-terminal intersect.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] FIRST(*E*) = {*b*, ε} and FIRST(*E* *a*) = {*b*, *a*}, so when the table is drawn, there is conflict under terminal *b* of production rule *S*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Left recursion will cause a FIRST/FIRST conflict with all alternatives.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The FIRST and FOLLOW set of a grammar rule overlap.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] With an empty string (ε) in the FIRST set, it is unknown which alternative to select.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] The FIRST set of *A* is {*a*, ε}, and the FOLLOW set is {*a*}.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Can be applied when two alternatives start with the same symbol like a FIRST/FIRST conflict.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Substituting a rule into another rule to remove indirect or FIRST/FOLLOW conflicts.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] Note that this may cause a FIRST/FIRST conflict.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/ll-parser] For a general method, see removing left recursion.
