[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In computer science, **LR parsers** are a type of bottom-up parser that analyse deterministic context-free languages in linear time.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] There are several variants of LR parsers: SLR parsers, LALR parsers, canonical LR(1) parsers, minimal LR(1) parsers, and generalized LR parsers (GLR parsers).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parsers can be generated by a parser generator from a formal grammar defining the syntax of the language to be parsed.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] They are widely used for the processing of computer languages.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] An LR parser (left-to-right, rightmost derivation in reverse) reads input text from left to right without backing up (this is true for most parsers), and produces a rightmost derivation in reverse: it does a bottom-up parse – not a top-down LL parse or ad-hoc parse.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The name "LR" is often followed by a numeric qualifier, as in "LR(1)" or sometimes "LR(*k*)".
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] To avoid backtracking or guessing, the LR parser is allowed to peek ahead at *k* lookahead input symbols before deciding how to parse earlier symbols.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Typically *k* is 1 and is not mentioned.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The name "LR" is often preceded by other qualifiers, as in "SLR" and "LALR".
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parsers are deterministic; they produce a single correct parse without guesswork or backtracking, in linear time.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This is ideal for computer languages, but LR parsers are not suited for human languages which need more flexible but inevitably slower methods.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Some methods which can parse arbitrary context-free languages (e.g., Cocke–Younger–Kasami, Earley, GLR) have worst-case performance of O(*n*3) time.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Other methods which backtrack or yield multiple parses may even take exponential time when they guess badly.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The above properties of **L**, **R**, and ***k*** are actually shared by all shift-reduce parsers, including precedence parsers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] But by convention, the LR name stands for the form of parsing invented by Donald Knuth, and excludes the earlier, less powerful precedence methods (for example Operator-precedence parser).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parsers can handle a larger range of languages and grammars than precedence parsers or top-down LL parsing.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This is because the LR parser waits until it has seen an entire instance of some grammar pattern before committing to what it has found.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] An LL parser has to decide or guess what it is seeing much sooner, when it has only seen the leftmost input symbol of that pattern.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] By a **sentence**, we mean a sentential form without any nonterminal symbols.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] A **right-sentential form** is any sentential form which may be obtained by beginning with the start symbol S and repeatedly applying productions rules only to the rightmost nonterminals.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The entire LR framework uses only right-sentential forms.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The prefix ${\color {blue}\alpha }$ is called the **viable prefix**, the substring ${\color {blue}\beta }$ is called the **handle**, and the string ${\color {blue}c_{1}c_{2}\dotsb c_{k}}$ is called the **lookahead**.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Observe that from the definition of "right-sentential form", we have that ${\color {blue}c_{1},c_{2},\dotsc ,c_{k}}$ , $\color {purple}\gamma$ and $\color {magenta}\gamma '$ are all terminal symbols.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Note that parsing consists of applying production rules *backwards*, which is called **reducing**.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Notably, it doesn't matter whether ${\color {purple}\gamma }={\color {magenta}\gamma '}$ or not.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Whether or not a CFG is $\operatorname {LR} (k)$ for a fixed k is decidable.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Whether there exists *any* k for which a CFG G is $\operatorname {LR} (k)$ is *not* decidable.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Any deterministic context-free language admits an $\operatorname {LR} (1)$ grammar, but this is in general neither small nor unique, and each of those grammars will result in a different parse tree for the same string.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] An LR parser scans and parses the input text in one forward pass over the text.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The parser builds up the parse tree incrementally, bottom up, and left to right, without guessing or backtracking.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] At every point in this pass, the parser has accumulated a list of subtrees or phrases of the input text that have been already parsed.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Those subtrees are not yet joined together because the parser has not yet reached the right end of the syntax pattern that will combine them.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] At step 6 in an example parse, only "A * 2" has been parsed, incompletely.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Only the shaded lower-left corner of the parse tree exists.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] None of the parse tree nodes numbered 7 and above exist yet.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Nodes 3, 4, and 6 are the roots of isolated subtrees for variable A, operator *, and number 2, respectively.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] These three root nodes are temporarily held in a parse stack.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The remaining unparsed portion of the input stream is "+ 1".
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] As with other shift-reduce parsers, an LR parser works by doing some combination of Shift steps and Reduce steps.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] If the input has no syntax errors, the parser continues with these steps until all of the input has been consumed and all of the parse trees have been reduced to a single tree representing an entire legal input.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parsers differ from other shift-reduce parsers in how they decide when to reduce, and how to pick between rules with similar endings.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] But the final decisions and the sequence of shift or reduce steps are the same.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Much of the LR parser's efficiency is from being deterministic.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] To avoid guessing, the LR parser often looks ahead (rightwards) at the next scanned symbol, before deciding what to do with previously scanned symbols.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The lexical scanner works one or more symbols ahead of the parser.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The **lookahead** symbols are the 'right-hand context' for the parsing decision.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Like other shift-reduce parsers, an LR parser lazily waits until it has scanned and parsed all parts of some construct before committing to what the combined construct is.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The parser then acts immediately on the combination instead of waiting any further.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In the parse tree example, the phrase A gets reduced to Value and then to Products in steps 1-3 as soon as lookahead * is seen, rather than waiting any later to organize those parts of the parse tree.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The decisions for how to handle A are based only on what the parser and scanner have already seen, without considering things that appear much later to the right.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Reductions reorganize the most recently parsed things, immediately to the left of the lookahead symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] So the list of already-parsed things acts like a stack.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The base or bottom of the stack is on the left and holds the leftmost, oldest parse fragment.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Every reduction step acts only on the rightmost, newest parse fragments.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This matches the stack top holding the parsed phrases "...
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The reduce step replaces this instance of the rule's right hand side, "Products * Value" by the rule's left hand side symbol, here a larger Products.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] If the parser builds complete parse trees, the three trees for inner Products, *, and Value are combined by a new tree root for Products.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Otherwise, semantic details from the inner Products and Value are output to some later compiler pass, or are combined and saved in the new Products symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In LR parsers, the shift and reduce decisions are potentially based on the entire stack of everything that has been previously parsed, not just on a single, topmost stack symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] If done in an unclever way, that could lead to very slow parsers that get slower and slower for longer inputs.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parsers do this with constant speed, by summarizing all the relevant left context information into a single number called the LR(0) **parser state**.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] For each grammar and LR analysis method, there is a fixed (finite) number of such states.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Besides holding the already-parsed symbols, the parse stack also remembers the state numbers reached by everything up to those points.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] At every parse step, the entire input text is divided into a stack of previously parsed phrases, a current look-ahead symbol, and the remaining unscanned text.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The parser's next action is determined by its current LR(0) state number (rightmost on the stack) and the lookahead symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In the steps below, all the black details are exactly the same as in other non-LR shift-reduce parsers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parser stacks add the state information in purple, summarizing the black phrases to their left on the stack and what syntax possibilities to expect next.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Users of an LR parser can usually ignore state information.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] These states are explained in a later section.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The parse stack begins by holding only initial state 0.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] When state 0 sees the lookahead *id*, it knows to shift that *id* onto the stack, and scan the next input symbol *****, and advance to state 9.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The states corresponding to the stacked phrases are 0, 4, and 5.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The current, rightmost state on the stack is state 5.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] When state 5 sees the lookahead *int*, it knows to shift that *int* onto the stack as its own phrase, and scan the next input symbol **+**, and advance to state 8.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] At step 12, all of the input stream has been consumed but only partially organized.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] by combining the stack's rightmost three phrases for Sums, **+**, and Products into one thing.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] State 3 itself doesn't know what the next state should be.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This is found by going back to state 0, just to the left of the phrase being reduced.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] When state 0 sees this new completed instance of a Sums, it advances to state 1 (again).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This consulting of older states is why they are kept on the stack, instead of keeping only the current state.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parsers are constructed from a grammar that formally defines the syntax of the input language as a set of patterns.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The grammar doesn't cover all language rules, such as the size of numbers, or the consistent use of names and their definitions in the context of the whole program.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parsers use a context-free grammar that deals just with local patterns of symbols.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The grammar's terminal symbols are the multi-character symbols or 'tokens' found in the input stream by a lexical scanner.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Here these include **+** ***** and *int* for any integer constant, and *id* for any identifier name, and *eof* for end of input file.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The grammar doesn't care what the *int* values or *id* spellings are, nor does it care about blanks or line breaks.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The grammar uses these terminal symbols but does not define them.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] They are always leaf nodes (at the bottom bushy end) of the parse tree.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The capitalized terms like Sums are nonterminal symbols.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] These are names for concepts or patterns in the language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] They are defined in the grammar and never occur themselves in the input stream.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] They are always internal nodes (above the bottom) of the parse tree.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] They only happen as a result of the parser applying some grammar rule.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Some nonterminals are defined with two or more rules; these are alternative patterns.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Rules can refer back to themselves, which are called *recursive*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This grammar uses recursive rules to handle repeated math operators.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Grammars for complete languages use recursive rules to handle lists, parenthesized expressions, and nested statements.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Any given computer language can be described by several different grammars.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] An LR(1) parser can handle many but not all common grammars.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] It is usually possible to manually modify a grammar so that it fits the limitations of LR(1) parsing and the generator tool.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The grammar for an LR parser must be unambiguous itself, or must be augmented by tie-breaking precedence rules.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This means there is only one correct way to apply the grammar to a given legal example of the language, resulting in a unique parse tree with just one meaning, and a unique sequence of shift/reduce actions for that example.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parsing is not a useful technique for human languages with ambiguous grammars that depend on the interplay of words.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Human languages are better handled by parsers like Generalized LR parser, the Earley parser, or the CYK algorithm that can simultaneously compute all possible parse trees in one pass.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The parser's program code is a simple generic loop that is the same for all grammars and languages.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The knowledge of the grammar and its syntactic implications are encoded into unchanging data tables called **parse tables** (or **parsing tables**).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Entries in a table show whether to shift or reduce (and by which grammar rule), for every legal combination of parser state and lookahead symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The parse tables also tell how to compute the next state, given just a current state and a next symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The parse tables are much larger than the grammar.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR tables are hard to accurately compute by hand for big grammars.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] So they are mechanically derived from the grammar by some parser generator tool like Bison.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Depending on how the states and parsing table are generated, the resulting parser is called either a **SLR** (simple LR) parser, **LALR** (look-ahead LR) parser, or canonical LR parser.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LALR parsers handle more grammars than SLR parsers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Canonical LR parsers handle even more grammars, but use many more states and much larger tables.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Each current LR(0) parser state has its own row.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Each possible next symbol has its own column.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Some combinations of state and next symbol are not possible for valid input streams.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] These blank cells trigger syntax error messages.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The **Action** left half of the table has columns for lookahead terminal symbols.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] These cells determine whether the next parser action is shift (to state *n*), or reduce (by grammar rule **r***n*).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The **Goto** right half of the table has columns for nonterminal symbols.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] These cells show which state to advance to, after some reduction's Left Hand Side has created an expected new instance of that symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This is like a shift action but for nonterminals; the lookahead terminal symbol is unchanged.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The table column "Current Rules" documents the meaning and syntax possibilities for each state, as worked out by the parser generator.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] It is not included in the actual tables used at parsing time.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The • (pink dot) marker shows where the parser is now, within some partially recognized grammar rules.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The things to the left of • have been parsed, and the things to the right are expected soon.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] A state has several such current rules if the parser has not yet narrowed possibilities down to a single rule.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Products begins with terminal symbols *int* or *id*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] If the lookahead is either of those, the parser shifts them in and advances to state 8 or 9, respectively.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] When a Products has been found, the parser advances to state 3 to accumulate the complete list of summands and find the end of rule r0.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] A Products can also begin with nonterminal Value.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] For any other lookahead or nonterminal, the parser announces a syntax error.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The choice between r1 and r3 can't be decided just from looking backwards at prior phrases.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The parser has to check the lookahead symbol to tell what to do.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] If the lookahead is *****, it is in rule 3, so the parser shifts in the ***** and advances to state 5.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] If the lookahead is *eof*, it is at the end of rule 1 and rule 0, so the parser is done.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In state 9 above, all the non-blank, non-error cells are for the same reduction r6.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Some parsers save time and table space by not checking the lookahead symbol in these simple cases.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Syntax errors are then detected somewhat later, after some harmless reductions, but still before the next shift action or parser decision.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Individual table cells must not hold multiple, alternative actions, otherwise the parser would be nondeterministic with guesswork and backtracking.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] If the grammar is not LR(1), some cells will have shift/reduce conflicts between a possible shift action and reduce action, or reduce/reduce conflicts between multiple grammar rules.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR(*k*) parsers resolve these conflicts (where possible) by checking additional lookahead symbols beyond the first.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The LR parser begins with a nearly empty parse stack containing just the start state 0, and with the lookahead holding the input stream's first scanned symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The topmost state on the parse stack is some state *s*, and the current lookahead is some terminal symbol *t*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Look up the next parser action from row *s* and column *t* of the Lookahead Action table.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] onto the parse stack and scan the next input symbol into the lookahead buffer.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] onto the parse stack as the new current state.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Remove the matched topmost L symbols (and parse trees and associated state numbers) from the parse stack.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] that was expecting an instance of the Lhs symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Join the L parse trees together as one parse tree with new root symbol Lhs.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Push the symbol and tree for Lhs onto the parse stack.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The lookahead and input stream remain unchanged.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parser stack usually stores just the LR(0) automaton states, as the grammar symbols may be derived from them (in the automaton, all input transitions to some state are marked with the same symbol, which is the symbol associated with this state).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Moreover, these symbols are almost never needed as the state is all that matters when making the parsing decision.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This section of the article can be skipped by most users of LR parser generators.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This shows how the parser got here, by seeing Sums then **+** while looking for a larger Sums.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The • marker has advanced beyond the beginning of the rule.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] It also shows how the parser expects to eventually complete the rule, by next finding a complete Products.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] But more details are needed on how to parse all the parts of that Products.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The partially parsed rules for a state are called its "core LR(0) items".
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The • marker is at the beginning of each of these added rules; the parser has not yet confirmed and parsed any part of them.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] These additional items are called the "closure" of the core items.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] For each nonterminal symbol immediately following a •, the generator adds the rules defining that symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This adds more • markers, and possibly different follower symbols.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This closure process continues until all follower symbols have been expanded.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The follower nonterminals for state 2 begins with Products.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The follower terminals are *int* and *id*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The kernel and closure items together show all possible legal ways to proceed from the current state to future states and complete phrases.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] If a follower symbol appears in only one item, it leads to a next state containing only one core item with the • marker advanced.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] If the same follower symbol appears in several items, the parser cannot yet tell which rule applies here.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] So that symbol leads to a next state that shows all remaining possibilities, again with the • marker advanced.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In words, that means if the parser has seen a single Products, it might be done, or it might still have even more things to multiply together.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] All the core items have the same symbol preceding the • marker; all transitions into this state are always with that same symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Some transitions will be to cores and states that have been enumerated already.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The generator starts with the grammar's goal rule.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] From there it keeps exploring known states and transitions until all needed states have been found.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] These states are called "LR(0)" states because they use a lookahead of *k*=0, i.e. no lookahead.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The only checking of input symbols occurs when the symbol is shifted in.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Checking of lookaheads for reductions is done separately by the parse table, not by the enumerated states themselves.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The parse table describes all possible LR(0) states and their transitions.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] An FSM is a simple engine for parsing simple unnested languages, without using a stack.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In this LR application, the FSM's modified "input language" has both terminal and nonterminal symbols, and covers any partially parsed stack snapshot of the full LR parse.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The parse stack shows a series of state transitions, from the start state 0, to state 4 and then on to 5 and current state 8.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The symbols on the parse stack are the shift or goto symbols for those transitions.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Another way to view this, is that the finite state machine can scan the stream "Products * *int* + 1" (without using yet another stack) and find the leftmost complete phrase that should be reduced next.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] How can a mere FSM do this when the original unparsed language has nesting and recursion and definitely requires an analyzer with a stack?
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The trick is that everything to the left of the stack top has already been fully reduced.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This eliminates all the loops and nesting from those phrases.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The FSM can ignore all the older beginnings of phrases, and track just the newest phrases that might be completed next.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The obscure name for this in LR theory is "viable prefix".
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The states and transitions give all the needed information for the parse table's shift actions and goto actions.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The generator also needs to calculate the expected lookahead sets for each reduce action.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In **SLR** parsers, these lookahead sets are determined directly from the grammar, without considering the individual states and transitions.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] For each nonterminal S, the SLR generator works out Follows(S), the set of all the terminal symbols which can immediately follow some occurrence of S.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In the parse table, each reduction to S uses Follow(S) as its LR(1) lookahead set.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Such follow sets are also used by generators for LL top-down parsers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] A grammar that has no shift/reduce or reduce/reduce conflicts when using Follow sets is called an SLR grammar.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] An SLR or LALR parser avoids having duplicate states.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] But this minimization is not necessary, and can sometimes create unnecessary lookahead conflicts.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] **Canonical LR** parsers use duplicated (or "split") states to better remember the left and right context of a nonterminal's use.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Each occurrence of a symbol S in the grammar can be treated independently with its own lookahead set, to help resolve reduction conflicts.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Unfortunately, this greatly magnifies the size of the parse tables if done for all parts of the grammar.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This splitting of states can also be done manually and selectively with any SLR or LALR parser, by making two or more named copies of some nonterminals.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] A grammar that is conflict-free for a canonical LR generator but has conflicts in an LALR generator is called LR(1) but not LALR(1), and not SLR.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] SLR, LALR, and canonical LR parsers make exactly the same shift and reduce decisions when the input stream is the correct language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] When the input has a syntax error, the LALR parser may do some additional (harmless) reductions before detecting the error than would the canonical LR parser.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This happens because the SLR and LALR parsers are using a generous superset approximation to the true, minimal lookahead symbols for that particular state.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parsers can generate somewhat helpful error messages for the first syntax error in a program, by simply enumerating all the terminal symbols that could have appeared next instead of the unexpected bad lookahead symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] But this does not help the parser work out how to parse the remainder of the input program to look for further, independent errors.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] If the parser recovers badly from the first error, it is very likely to mis-parse everything else and produce a cascade of unhelpful spurious error messages.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In the yacc and bison parser generators, the parser has an ad hoc mechanism to abandon the current statement, discard some parsed phrases and lookahead tokens surrounding the error, and resynchronize the parse at some reliable statement-level delimiter like semicolons or braces.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This often works well for allowing the parser and compiler to look over the rest of the program.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Many syntactic coding errors are simple typos or omissions of a trivial symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Some LR parsers attempt to detect and automatically repair these common cases.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The parser enumerates every possible single-symbol insertion, deletion, or substitution at the error point.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The compiler does a trial parse with each change to see if it worked okay.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] (This requires backtracking to snapshots of the parse stack and input stream, normally unneeded by the parser.) Some best repair is picked.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This gives a very helpful error message and resynchronizes the parse well.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] However, the repair is not trustworthy enough to permanently modify the input file.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Repair of syntax errors is easiest to do consistently in parsers (like LR) that have parse tables and an explicit data stack.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The LR parser generator decides what should happen for each combination of parser state and lookahead symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] These decisions are usually turned into read-only data tables that drive a generic parser loop that is grammar- and state-independent.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] But there are also other ways to turn those decisions into an active parser.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Some LR parser generators create separate tailored program code for each state, rather than a parse table.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] These parsers can run several times faster than the generic parser loop in table-driven parsers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The fastest parsers use generated assembler code.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In the recursive ascent parser variation, the explicit parse stack structure is also replaced by the implicit stack used by subroutine calls.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Reductions terminate several levels of subroutine calls, which is clumsy in most languages.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] So recursive ascent parsers are generally slower, less obvious, and harder to hand-modify than recursive descent parsers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Another variation replaces the parse table by pattern-matching rules in non-procedural languages such as Prolog.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parsers were invented by Donald Knuth in 1965 as an efficient generalization of precedence parsers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Knuth proved that LR parsers were the most general-purpose parsers possible that would still be efficient in the worst cases.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In other words, if a language was reasonable enough to allow an efficient one-pass parser, it could be described by an LR(*k*) grammar.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] And that grammar could always be mechanically transformed into an equivalent (but larger) LR(1) grammar.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] So an LR(1) parsing method was, in theory, powerful enough to handle any reasonable language.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In practice, the natural grammars for many programming languages are close to being LR(1).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The canonical LR parsers described by Knuth had too many states and very big parse tables that were impractically large for the limited memory of computers of that era.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] LR parsing became practical when Frank DeRemer invented SLR and LALR parsers with much fewer states.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] For full details on LR theory and how LR parsers are derived from grammars, see *The Theory of Parsing, Translation, and Compiling, Volume 1* (Aho and Ullman).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Earley parsers apply the techniques and • notation of LR parsers to the task of generating all possible parses for ambiguous grammars such as for human languages.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] While LR(*k*) grammars have equal generative power for all *k*≥1, the case of LR(0) grammars is slightly different.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] A language *L* is said to have the *prefix property* if no word in *L* is a proper prefix of another word in *L*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] A language *L* has an LR(0) grammar if and only if *L* is a deterministic context-free language with the prefix property.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] As a consequence, a language *L* is deterministic context-free if and only if *L*$ has an LR(0) grammar, where "$" is not a symbol of *L*'s alphabet.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The **goto table** is indexed by a state of the parser and a nonterminal and simply indicates what the next state of the parser will be if it has recognized a certain nonterminal.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This table is important to find out the next state after every reduction.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] After a reduction, the next state is found by looking up the **goto table** entry for top of the stack (i.e. current state) and the reduced rule's LHS (i.e. non-terminal).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The table below illustrates each step in the process.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Here the state refers to the element at the top of the stack (the right-most element), and the next action is determined by referring to the action table above.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] A $ is appended to the input string to denote the end of the stream.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The first symbol from the input string that the parser sees is '1'.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] To find the next action (shift, reduce, accept or error), the action table is indexed with the current state (the "current state" is just whatever is on the top of the stack), which in this case is 0, and the current input symbol, which is '1'.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The action table specifies a shift to state 2, and so state 2 is pushed onto the stack (again, all the state information is in the stack, so "shifting to state 2" is the same as pushing 2 onto the stack).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] For the sake of explaining the symbol (e.g., '1', B) is shown that caused the transition to the next state, although strictly speaking it is not part of the stack.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In state 2, the action table says to reduce with grammar rule 5 (regardless of what terminal the parser sees on the input stream), which means that the parser has just recognized the right-hand side of rule 5.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In this case, the parser writes 5 to the output stream, pops one state from the stack (since the right-hand side of the rule has one symbol), and pushes on the stack the state from the cell in the goto table for state 0 and B, i.e., state 4.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] However, in state 4, the action table says the parser should now reduce with rule 3.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] So it writes 3 to the output stream, pops one state from the stack, and finds the new state in the goto table for state 0 and E, which is state 3.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The resulting stack can be interpreted as the history of a finite-state machine that has just read a nonterminal E followed by a terminal '+'.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The transition table of this automaton is defined by the shift actions in the action table and the goto actions in the goto table.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The stack corresponds with a list of states of a finite automaton that has read a nonterminal E, followed by a '+' and then a nonterminal B.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] In state 8 the parser always performs a reduce with rule 2.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The top 3 states on the stack correspond with the 3 symbols in the right-hand side of rule 2.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Finally, the parser reads a '$' (end of input symbol) from the input stream, which means that according to the action table (the current state is 3) the parser accepts the input string.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The rule numbers that will then have been written to the output stream will be [5, 3, 5, 2] which is indeed a rightmost derivation of the string "1 + 1" in reverse.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The construction of these parsing tables is based on the notion of *LR(0) items* (simply called *items* here) which are grammar rules with a special dot added somewhere in the right-hand side.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Rules of the form *A* → ε have only a single item *A* → •.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The item E → E • + B, for example, indicates that the parser has recognized a string corresponding with E on the input stream and now expects to read a '+' followed by another string corresponding with B.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] It is usually not possible to characterize the state of the parser with a single item because it may not know in advance which rule it is going to use for reduction.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] For example, if there is also a rule E → E * B then the items E → E • + B and E → E • * B will both apply after a string corresponding with E has been read.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Therefore, it is convenient to characterize the state of the parser by a set of items, in this case the set { E → E • + B, E → E • * B }.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] An item with a dot before a nonterminal, such as E → E + • B, indicates that the parser expects to parse the nonterminal B next.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] To ensure the item set contains all possible rules the parser may be in the midst of parsing, it must include all items describing how B itself will be parsed.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] This means that if there are rules such as B → 1 and B → 0 then the item set must also include the items B → • 1 and B → • 0.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] Thus, any set of items can be extended by recursively adding all the appropriate items until all nonterminals preceded by dots are accounted for.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The minimal extension is called the *closure* of an item set and written as **clos**(*I*) where *I* is an item set.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] It is these closed item sets that are taken as the states of the parser, although only the ones that are actually reachable from the begin state will be included in the tables.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] where S is a new start symbol and E the old start symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] The parser will use this rule for reduction exactly when it has accepted the whole input string.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p01] It is for this augmented grammar that the item sets and the transitions between them will be determined.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] The first step of constructing the tables consists of determining the transitions between the closed item sets.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] These transitions will be determined as if we are considering a finite automaton that can read terminals as well as nonterminals.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] The boldfaced "**+**" in front of an item indicates the items that were added for the closure (not to be confused with the mathematical '+' operator which is a terminal).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] The original items without a "**+**" are called the *kernel* of the item set.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] Starting at the begin state (S0), all of the states that can be reached from this state are now determined.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] The possible transitions for an item set can be found by looking at the symbols (terminals and nonterminals) found following the dots; in the case of item set 0 those symbols are the terminals '0' and '1' and the nonterminals E and B.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] For each item in *S*, move the dot to the right of *x*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] The closure does not add new items in all cases - in the new sets above, for example, there are no nonterminals following the dot.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] Above procedure is continued until no more new item sets are found.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] For the item sets 1, 2, and 4 there will be no transitions since the dot is not in front of any symbol.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] For item set 3 though, we have dots in front of terminals '*' and '+'.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] For item set 5, the terminals '0' and '1' and the nonterminal B must be considered, but the resulting closed item sets for the terminals are equal to already found item sets 1 and 2, respectively.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] For item set 6, the terminal '0' and '1' and the nonterminal B must be considered, but as before, the resulting item sets for the terminals are equal to the already found item sets 1 and 2.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] These final item sets 7 and 8 have no symbols beyond their dots so no more new item sets are added, so the item generating procedure is complete.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] The finite automaton, with item sets as its states is shown below.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] The columns for the terminals are copied to the action table as shift actions.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] An extra column for '$' (end of input) is added to the action table.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] An *acc* action is added to the '$' column for each item set that contains an item of the form S → w • eof.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] If an item set *i* contains an item of the form *A* → *w* • and *A* → *w* is rule *m* with *m* > 0 then the row for state *i* in the action table is completely filled with the reduce action r*m*.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] The reader may verify that these steps produce the action and goto table presented earlier.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] Only step 4 of the above procedure produces reduce actions, and so all reduce actions must occupy an entire table row, causing the reduction to occur regardless of the next symbol in the input stream.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] This is why these are LR(0) parse tables: they don't do any lookahead (that is, they look ahead zero symbols) before deciding which reduction to perform.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] A grammar that needs lookahead to disambiguate reductions would require a parse table row containing different reduce actions in different columns, and the above procedure is not capable of creating such rows.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] Refinements to the **LR**(0) table construction procedure (such as SLR and LALR) are capable of constructing reduce actions that do not occupy entire rows.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] Therefore, they are capable of parsing more grammars than LR(0) parsers.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] The automaton is constructed in such a way that it is guaranteed to be deterministic.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] However, when reduce actions are added to the action table it can happen that the same cell is filled with a reduce action and a shift action (a *shift-reduce conflict*) or with two different reduce actions (a *reduce-reduce conflict*).
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] However, it can be shown that when this happens the grammar is not an LR(0) grammar.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] A classic real-world example of a shift-reduce conflict is the dangling else problem.
[src:compilers-and-parsing/lr-parser-p02] There is a shift-reduce conflict in this item set: when constructing the action table according to the rules above, the cell for [item set 1, terminal '1'] contains **s1** (shift to state 1) **and r2** (reduce with grammar rule 2).
